Although the earliest text in which it occurs goes back only to the eighth century, it is probable that it is much more ancient.

It is evident‚ moreover‚ that the place assigned to the Kyrie eleison in the Roman Litany is not that given to it in the Eastern Ghurches. In the Roman Litany it occurs at the beginning and the end, and is said alternately by the precentor and the congregation. In the East it formed the people's response to the petitions in the Diaconal Litany.
